{"key":"processedPost-9031877","value":{"id":9031877,"first":9030085,"last":9031877,"when":1223226345,"utime":"10/05/08 08:05 PM","cleanedPost":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>Cakes said:</strong><br />I know it slows down growth, but I can't figure out why.&nbsp; Mycelium grows just fine in LC solution and agar </blockquote><br />Not quite.&nbsp; LC is extremely slow, perhaps ten to fifty times slower than properly hydrated grains, and that's the reason I recommend against making LC solutions.&nbsp; A rye grain quart jar will fully colonize in ten days to two weeks, and in that time, you'll perhaps have a tiny little blob of mycelium in an LC, which is only a minute fraction of the amount of mycelium you'll grow in a jar of grains.<br />If the grains are too wet, you cause the same problem that makes LC inferior.&nbsp; Mycelium needs air to expand rapidly.<br />Mycelium grows fast on agar because it only grows on the surface where it has plenty of air, not through the middle of the media.<br />RR"}}